WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.667 --> 00:00:04.963
Hi and welcome back to the Variational Quantum Eigensolver course series.

2
00:00:05.380 --> 00:00:10.093
My name is Victoria Lipinska and in this video we will dive into how to represent

3
00:00:10.093 --> 00:00:14.264
a given VQE problem in a way that the quantum computer understands.

4
00:00:14.973 --> 00:00:18.685
Typically, a quantum chemistry problem is expressed in terms of energies

5
00:00:18.685 --> 00:00:19.686
of the system.

6
00:00:19.686 --> 00:00:24.357
We refer to the operator, which describes these energies as the Hamiltonian.

7
00:00:24.983 --> 00:00:26.776
First, we need to quantize it.

8
00:00:26.776 --> 00:00:29.988
That is express it in the language of quantum chemistry,

9
00:00:29.988 --> 00:00:32.615
which is formally called second quantization.

10
00:00:33.199 --> 00:00:36.286
If the Hamiltonian describes fermion interactions, for example,

11
00:00:36.286 --> 00:00:40.582
energy of electrons in spin orbitals, we refer to this

12
00:00:40.582 --> 00:00:44.919
as fermionic Hamiltonian, and it will be our starting point today.

13
00:00:45.545 --> 00:00:48.715
Qubits, however, have their own language.

14
00:00:48.715 --> 00:00:53.011
The operators in the qubit world are described by the Pauli operators.

15
00:00:53.637 --> 00:00:57.099
So our focus here is to express the fermionic operators

16
00:00:57.099 --> 00:01:00.060
in terms of qubit operators.

17
00:01:00.060 --> 00:01:02.855
There is a simple one-to-one correspondence between

18
00:01:02.855 --> 00:01:05.524
the zero and one states for fermions and qubits.

19
00:01:05.858 --> 00:01:10.154
So the mapping between the states is also straightforward.

20
00:01:10.571 --> 00:01:10.696
However, the mapping of the operators is slightly more complex.

21
00:01:10.695 --> 00:01:14.074
But fermionic Hamiltonians are expressed with creation and

22
00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:16.034
annihilation operators.

23
00:01:16.034 --> 00:01:20.288
So our job is to make it easier for a quantum computer to understand

24
00:01:20.413 --> 00:01:21.998
the Hamiltonian.

25
00:01:21.998 --> 00:01:26.169
We will use mathematical tools to map a fermionic Hamiltonian

26
00:01:26.377 --> 00:01:28.838
into a qubit Hamiltonian with gates.

27
00:01:29.297 --> 00:01:32.175
So in other words, we will be translating between

28
00:01:32.175 --> 00:01:36.429
the quantum chemistry language and quantum computing language.

29
00:01:36.429 --> 00:01:39.766
Imagine two chains, one with fermions,

30
00:01:39.766 --> 00:01:41.935
so quantum chemistry language.

31
00:01:41.935 --> 00:01:44.979
And one with qubits, so quantum computing language.

32
00:01:45.355 --> 00:01:48.566
At the first glance, the mapping seems straightforward, right?

33
00:01:48.817 --> 00:01:52.195
In both cases, we see systems with two levels.

34
00:01:52.737 --> 00:01:56.491
For fermions, we have either one fermion in the state

35
00:01:56.491 --> 00:01:58.785
or no fermion at all.

36
00:01:58.785 --> 00:02:01.746
And for qubits, we have either state 0 or state 1.

37
00:02:02.205 --> 00:02:04.916
However, it's more nuanced than that.

38
00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:09.504
The difference between a chain of qubits and a chain of fermions

39
00:02:09.712 --> 00:02:14.467
is something very fundamental in physics: what we call exchange symmetry.

40
00:02:15.135 --> 00:02:18.388
Two fermions can never occupy the same state.

41
00:02:18.388 --> 00:02:22.183
However, for a chain of qubits, this is completely different.

42
00:02:22.725 --> 00:02:25.603
Two qubits can both be in the same state,

43
00:02:25.603 --> 00:02:28.064
as a qubit is not a fermion.

44
00:02:28.064 --> 00:02:28.273
We must now find a way to translate between the two chains.

45
00:02:28.273 --> 00:02:32.694
already in 1928, two researchers, Jordan and Wigner,

46
00:02:32.902 --> 00:02:36.489
showed that fermionic operators for the whole chain

47
00:02:36.906 --> 00:02:40.660
can be represented exactly in terms of qubit operators.

48
00:02:41.411 --> 00:02:44.372
This is the most straightforward mapping for a quantum computer.

49
00:02:44.706 --> 00:02:47.959
For example, one can use that to map an occupation

50
00:02:47.959 --> 00:02:51.462
of an orbital to the spin of one qubit.

51
00:02:51.462 --> 00:02:57.051
Practically, this mapping for a Hamiltonian results results in a weighted sum of Pauli operators.

52
00:02:57.468 --> 00:03:00.430
This is a very important fact, which I'd like you to keep in mind,

53
00:03:00.805 --> 00:03:04.559
and we will come back to this in the next module where we will talk

54
00:03:04.559 --> 00:03:08.646
about how variational circuits are executed on the quantum computer.

55
00:03:09.397 --> 00:03:12.192
The above mapping means that if we had, for example,

56
00:03:12.734 --> 00:03:18.072
14 fermionic operators, we will map the problem onto 14 qubits.

57
00:03:18.531 --> 00:03:22.410
Luckily, there exist clever ways to reduce the numbers of qubits

58
00:03:22.619 --> 00:03:27.457
and use less quantum resources to get a better performance from a quantum computer.

59
00:03:28.250 --> 00:03:31.420
Typically, in a molecular system, we will know

60
00:03:31.420 --> 00:03:34.881
some physical symmetries of the Hamiltonian,

61
00:03:35.215 --> 00:03:39.219
for instance, the total number of electrons is fixed.

62
00:03:39.553 --> 00:03:42.806
This information can be used to reduce the size of the problem

63
00:03:43.098 --> 00:03:44.975
without losing any relevant information.

64
00:03:45.559 --> 00:03:49.771
We call this technique the active space reduction.

65
00:03:50.313 --> 00:03:56.903
This allows for the reduction of number of resources, namely, number of qubits,

66
00:03:56.903 --> 00:04:00.657
before the qubit mapping like Jordan-Wigner transformation.

67
00:04:01.658 --> 00:04:04.327
This step calculates an effective Hamiltonian

68
00:04:04.535 --> 00:04:07.497
and allows us to use less qubits as a result.

69
00:04:08.081 --> 00:04:10.124
For our example with 14 orbitals,

70
00:04:10.333 --> 00:04:14.128
this technique reduces the number of qubits to just six.

71
00:04:15.463 --> 00:04:18.257
We can now go even further with these reductions.

72
00:04:18.841 --> 00:04:20.718
We can use different mappings,

73
00:04:20.718 --> 00:04:23.805
which are a little bit more elaborate than Jordan-Wigner.

74
00:04:24.430 --> 00:04:27.392
The most common example is the parity mapping.

75
00:04:27.725 --> 00:04:32.146
Parity mapping doesn't map occupation of the orbitals on the qubits,

76
00:04:32.438 --> 00:04:35.650
but rather the parity of orbitals onto single qubits.

77
00:04:36.859 --> 00:04:39.654
We will not go into the mathematical details here,

78
00:04:39.946 --> 00:04:44.409
but what's important to know is that this mapping contains additional

79
00:04:44.409 --> 00:04:47.662
redundancies which can be utilized to remove two more qubits.

80
00:04:48.538 --> 00:04:53.960
Therefore, our example with 14 orbitals, reduces from 14 qubits

81
00:04:54.210 --> 00:04:58.548
to 6 qubits with active space reduction and then to 4 qubits

82
00:04:58.548 --> 00:05:01.717
with the two qubit reduction in the parity mapping.

83
00:05:02.718 --> 00:05:06.180
Let us briefly mention one more transformation.

84
00:05:06.806 --> 00:05:09.684
Another commonly used mapping between the fermionic

85
00:05:09.684 --> 00:05:13.229
and qubit representation is the Bravyi-Kitaev transformation.

86
00:05:13.563 --> 00:05:16.942
The Bravyi-Kitaev transformation uses qubits to encode the information

87
00:05:17.025 --> 00:05:21.863
about both the occupation number and the parity of the quantum state.

88
00:05:22.447 --> 00:05:25.158
The Bravyi-Kitaev transformation combines occupation number and parity information

89
00:05:25.158 --> 00:05:28.744
for a molecular orbital basis of size N,

90
00:05:28.745 --> 00:05:31.456
there are again N and qubits used.

91
00:05:31.456 --> 00:05:34.917
However, the information stored within each qubit

92
00:05:34.917 --> 00:05:38.296
now varies depending on which qubit it is.

93
00:05:38.963 --> 00:05:42.342
That is when the index of the qubit is even,

94
00:05:42.342 --> 00:05:44.844
its stores the occupation number of the corresponding

95
00:05:44.844 --> 00:05:48.014
orbital number as in the Jordan-Wigner mapping.

96
00:05:48.639 --> 00:05:52.560
When the qubit index is odd, the qubit stores a parity of a particular

97
00:05:52.643 --> 00:05:57.482
set of occupation numbers. Bravyi-Kitaev transformation is the most efficient

98
00:05:57.648 --> 00:06:01.444
when the number of qubits approaches the power of two.

99
00:06:01.861 --> 00:06:05.698
The Bravyi-Kitaev mapping combines the advantages from the Jordan-Wigner

100
00:06:05.907 --> 00:06:08.075
and the parity transformations.

101
00:06:08.076 --> 00:06:11.746
It reduces the number of qubits that each Hamiltonian term acts on,

102
00:06:14.665 --> 00:06:17.585
It's important for quantum simulation as terms

103
00:06:17.585 --> 00:06:20.546
acting on the large number of qubits in the Hamiltonian

104
00:06:20.755 --> 00:06:25.051
require longer circuits for their simulation.

105
00:06:25.051 --> 00:06:26.844
This means that the circuit depth

106
00:06:26.844 --> 00:06:30.681
is reduced with the Bravyi-Kitaev transformation and in general

107
00:06:30.681 --> 00:06:34.435
we can obtain better results with hardware.

108
00:06:34.435 --> 00:06:37.480
This is an improvement over the Jordan-Wigner transformation

109
00:06:37.647 --> 00:06:41.359
which results in order of N qubit Hamiltonian.

110
00:06:42.193 --> 00:06:45.446
So, in this video we explored methods to map

111
00:06:45.530 --> 00:06:48.324
a fermionic Hamiltonian onto a qubit Hamiltonian.

112
00:06:48.658 --> 00:06:52.245
In the next one we'll see how to best select the state

113
00:06:52.745 --> 00:06:55.081
and a variational form or a circuit.

114
00:06:55.540 --> 00:06:56.748
We'll see you there.
